Real-Time Performance and Computational Efficiency in SLAM: A Survey

Introduction:
SLAM (Simultaneous Localization and Mapping) is a fundamental area of research in robotics and computer vision that involves estimating the position of a device in a 3D environment while simultaneously creating a map of that environment. With the increasing demand for real-time performance, computational efficiency has become a crucial aspect of SLAM systems. This section will explore the current state of hardware and software architecture for SLAM, data structures and algorithms used in visual-inertial SLAM, computational complexity and optimization techniques, and relevant publications that address these topics.

Hardware and Software Architecture: Real-Time Performance and Computational Efficiency in SLAM
SLAM systems require a significant amount of computational resources to process the vast amounts of sensor data. To achieve real-time performance, researchers have focused on developing specialized hardware and software architectures. For example, FPGA-based accelerators can significantly improve the performance of ORB-SLAM \cite{orbslam} by reducing the computation required for feature extraction and matching. Moreover, parallelizing the SLAM algorithm using multiple processing units or cores can further enhance its computational efficiency \cite{parsla}.

Data Structures and Algorithms: Data Structures and Algorithms for Visual-Inertial SLAM
Visual-inertial SLAM combines visual and inertial sensors to estimate the position of a device in 3D space. The choice of data structures and algorithms can significantly impact the performance of these systems. For instance, using a compact representation of the map, such as a grid or a tree, can reduce the computational complexity of the algorithm while maintaining its accuracy \cite{compact}. Moreover, optimizing the sensor fusion process by selecting the most informative sensors and developing efficient feature extraction algorithms can improve the overall performance of the system \cite{sensorfusion}.

Computational Complexity and Optimization Techniques: Computational Complexity and Optimization Techniques in SLAM
SLAM algorithms are computationally demanding, particularly when dealing with large amounts of sensor data. To address this challenge, researchers have proposed various optimization techniques such as iterative closest point (ICP) \cite{icp} and non-linear least squares (NLLS) \cite{nlls}. These techniques can significantly reduce the computational complexity of the algorithm while maintaining its accuracy. Moreover, using approximate algorithms or reducing the number of features used in the SLAM algorithm can also improve its computational efficiency \cite{approximate}.

